  "prompt": "What does it mean when you have blood clots but no period?",
  "response": "Experiencing blood clots without a period can be concerning and may be due to several different reasons. Here are some possible causes:\n\n1. **Irregular Menstrual Cycle**: Sometimes, what appears to be a period might be spotting or irregular bleeding. This could be due to hormonal imbalances, stress, or other factors affecting your menstrual cycle.\n\n2. **Pregnancy Complications**: Blood clots can be a sign of miscarriage or ectopic pregnancy. If you suspect you might be pregnant and experience clotting, it's essential to seek medical attention immediately.\n\n3. **Ovulation Bleeding**: Some women experience spotting or light bleeding during ovulation, which can sometimes include small clots.\n\n4. **Uterine or Cervical Issues**: Conditions like fibroids, polyps, or cervical dysplasia can cause irregular bleeding and clotting.\n\n5. **Hormonal Contraceptives**: Starting, stopping, or changing birth control methods can lead to irregular bleeding and clotting.\n\n6. **Infections or STDs**: Certain infections or sexually transmitted diseases can cause irregular bleeding.\n\n7. **Bleeding Disorders**: Some bleeding disorders can cause abnormal bleeding and clotting.\n\n8. **Endometriosis or Adenomyosis**: These conditions involve the endometrial tissue and can cause irregular bleeding and clotting.\n\nIf you are experiencing blood clots without a period, it's important to consult a healthcare provider to determine the cause and receive appropriate treatment. They may recommend tests such as a pregnancy test, pelvic exam, ultrasound, or blood work to diagnose the issue.",
